<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-916-680  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 916 680.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 27 1989 v23 n48 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Quantum gets a little egg on disk-drive face. (Quantum Corpproduct failures)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pastore, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Quantum Corp, a major OEM supplier of hard disk drives for theApple Macintosh, has received much publicity as a result of thefailure of its new 1-inch-high drives.andP;  The company was at firstindifferent to user reports of frequent crashes; then, the companyacknowledged the problem and initiated a repair program which manyusers fear has only caused more problems.andP;  Quantum determined thatthe drive lubricant had somehow thickened and designed a PROM fixthat directs additional power and seek motions to the actuatorarm.andP;  Some users complained that drives equipped with the new PROMmade loud chattering noises and were significantly slower.andO;Company officials say that the additional seeks do cause somenoise, but that this should disappear as the lubricant thins out.andO;Quantum blames Apple for not adequately reporting the details ofthe fix to customers; Apple denies these charges and says it hascooperated with Quantum.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Quantum Corp. (product recall).andO;Ticker:    QNTM.andO;Topic:     Product FailuresDefectsPROMRepair.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>